                      img(src='/img/speakers/joe-pettersson.jpg')
                  h3 JavaScript Security: myths, fallacies and anti-patterns
                  p.talk-summary
                    | I've worked on some very sensitive front-end codebases
                    | (banks, pharma, defence et al) and as a consequence
                    | I've come across every type of good and bad practice.
                    | In this talk I'll share some of those experiences and
                    | talk about the part security plays in delivering high
                    | quality client-side JavaScript, including:
                    br
                    br
                    | * Why you don't control your run-time environment and
                    | why that's such a problem.
                    br
                    | * Some inherent problems with JavaScript's security
                    | model and design
                    br
                    | * Writing secure API's with that in mind
                    br
                    | * Exposing and implementing countermeasures for
                    | common attacks in highly sensitive codebases
                    br
                    | * Patterns and anti-patterns in front-end penetration
                    | testing and auditing
                    br
                    | * Why security is so important to high quality code,
                    | and why you're probably not thinking about it enough
                    br
                    br
                    | Hopefully, by the end of the talk, you'll be able to
                    | take away some the lessons I've learnt from the best of
                    | these highly secure front-end codebases, and maybe how
                    | you can stop yours failing quite as spectacularly as
                    | some of the worst ones have.
                td.time 11:25
